## Why this hook / signal (feasibility)
- _save_op is the single choke point for op publishing (create_call:1412 and
  _save_object:2574 / weave.publish). Least invasive: one call added.
- Gate on get_ref(op) is None BEFORE _save_object_basic sets the ref. A
  module-scope op is saved once (set_ref runs synchronously in _save_object_basic
  even though the digest is a Future), so subsequent create_calls short-circuit
  via map_to_refs and never re-count → zero false positives. A loop-decorated op
  is a NEW ref-less wrapper each iteration → same key accumulates.
- Key on op.resolve_fn.__code__ (the USER function), NOT the wrapper — every
  wrapper shares op.py wrapper code. Include op.name because anonymous ops
  (_build_anonymous_op) all share one resolve_fn code location and must not
  collide by name. resolve_fn/__code__ missing → skip (handles builtins).
- Counting *distinct digests* (true versions) client-side is NOT cleanly
  feasible: digests are Futures; reading them blocks on the server. Publish-count
  per location is the robust proxy — if digests differ it's real explosion; if
  the server dedupes it's still wasteful round-trips, and the same fix applies.
  So the client-side signal IS feasible without fragile heuristics; did not need
  the server-side fallback.
- Cheapest filter first (get_ref) so steady-state traced calls pay only one
  getattr; settings read and locking happen only on genuinely fresh publishes.

