## Hints & warnings
- Threshold=50 is deliberately far above hand-written re-decoration but far below
  127k; a count that high from ONE source line is unambiguously a loop. Test
  imports OP_VERSION_EXPLOSION_WARN_THRESHOLD so it tracks the constant.
- State is process-global (module-level) and mutated under a Lock without any
  `global` rebinding (avoids PLW0603). It survives across weave.init() calls;
  that's fine (a module-scope op contributes count 1 per client, well under
  threshold).
- Notebook cell re-runs / heavily-parametrized tests that redefine an op at the
  SAME source line >50 times will legitimately trip the (advisory) warning —
  acceptable and opt-out.
- Did NOT need to touch the op() decorator (op.py) — counting definitions there
  would over-warn (defines that are never called publish nothing) and has no
  client. Publishing is the correct place.

